EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to domestic violence; establishing the Hope Card Program for
applicants who have been granted an extended order for protection
against domestic violence; providing a penalty; and providing other
matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law authorizes a person to file an application for a temporary or extended order
2 for protection against domestic violence. (NRS 33.017-33.100) Section 1 of this bill
3 establishes the Hope Card Program, which will be developed and administered by the Office
4 of the Attorney General, after consultation and in coordination with the district courts and
5 justice courts, to provide to an applicant who has been granted an extended order for
6 protection against domestic violence, upon request, a Hope Card that provides proof of the
7 granting of such an extended order. Section 1 also prohibits a person from knowingly
8 presenting a fraudulent or expired Hope Card to another person with the specific intent to
9 falsely represent that the person is protected by an extended order.
10 Section 2 of this bill makes a conforming change to apply the definitions in existing law
11 to section 1.
12 Section 3 of this bill requires an applicant for an extended order for protection against
13 domestic violence to indicate in the application whether the applicant is requesting a Hope
14 Card.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 33 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
2 section to read as follows:
3 1. The Hope Card Program, which is intended to provide to an applicant
4 who has been granted an extended order, upon request, a Hope Card that
5 provides proof of the granting of the extended order, is hereby established. The

