1 Office of the Attorney General shall, after consultation and in coordination with
2 the district courts and justice courts, develop and administer the Hope Card
3 Program.
4 2. The Hope Card Program must ensure than an applicant who has been
5 granted an extended order and who has requested a Hope Card pursuant to NRS
6 33.020 is provided with the Hope Card as soon as practicable, but not more than
7 10 business days after the extended order is granted.
8 3. The Office of the Attorney General shall not charge any fee for providing
9 a Hope Card pursuant to this section.
10 4. A Hope Card that is provided to an applicant for an extended order
11 pursuant to this section:
12 (a) Is valid until the date on which the extended order expires;
13 (b) May be issued in the form of a tangible, wallet-sized card or a digital
14 card, or both;
15 (c) Must be in a format established by the Office of the Attorney General that
16 contains substantially the following information:
17 (1) The name and date of birth of the applicant;
18 (2) Information relating to the extended order, including, without
19 limitation, the court that granted the extended order, the case number, the date
20 on which the extended order was granted and the date on which the extended
21 order expires;
22 (3) The date on which the Hope Card is issued and the date on which the
23 Hope Card expires; and
24 (4) Any other information that the Office of the Attorney General deems
25 appropriate [.] , which may include, without limitation:
26 (I) The name and description of each additional person or animal
27 protected by the extended order;
28 (II) The name and date of birth of the adverse party;
29 (III) A physical description of the adverse party, including, without
30 limitation, height, weight, hair color and eye color;
31 (IV) A photograph of the adverse party, if available; and
32 (V) The telephone number for the United States National Domestic
33 Violence Hotline.
34 5. A person who knowingly presents a fraudulent or expired Hope Card to
35 another person with the specific intent to falsely represent that the person is
36 protected by an extended order is guilty of a misdemeanor.
